Yeah, after seeing the backend, I don't think the frontend code you pasted is the culprit.

The behavior you described:

Device A likes → 1 Device B likes → 0 Device C likes → 1

is almost a textbook symptom of IP-based toggling.

Look at your backend again:



const rawIP = req.ip || req.connection.remoteAddress || 'unknown';
const ipHash = crypto.createHash('sha256').update(rawIP).digest('hex');

Then:



const { data: existing } = await supabase
  .from('message_likes')
  .select('id')
  .eq('message_id', id)
  .eq('ip_hash', ipHash)
  .maybeSingle();

If the IP already exists:



if (existing) {
  // unlike
}

So if all your devices are on the same WiFi, they all share the same public IP.

To Whispr:



iPhone     = 102.xxx.xxx.xxx
Android    = 102.xxx.xxx.xxx
Laptop     = 102.xxx.xxx.xxx

All identical.

